The course addresses the following topics from the philosophy of science perspective:
the concept of science, various ways of defining science, science and pseudo-science, philosophy and science, most significant philosophical theories of science (inductivism, falsificationism, activity-based accounts, structure-based accounts), comparison between natural, humanitarian and social sciences; methodological topics like what is a concept, fact, model, hypothesis, laws of nature, theory, explanation, observation, experiment, objectivity; the concepts of truth, objectivism, knowledge and values; science in society.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The aim is to introduce the main concepts, problems and arguments in philosophy of science and provide some analysis of those, as well as to develop the students' skills of analysis, argumentation, and academic presentation, both orally and in writing.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  A student who has successfully passed the course: 1) knows and is able to apply central concepts of philosophy of science; 2) knows the most significant theoretical accounts, arguments and views in philosophy of science; 3) knows the main problems of philosophy of science; 4) is able to analyse cases from her/his own specialty in terms of philosophy of science; 5) is able to provide critical analysis of main problems and to (re)construct the main problems in philosophy of science; 6) is able to express one's knowledge in the field correctly in writing and oral presentations.
